            <div type="note">
                <head><persName corresp="CTR">Charles Thomas Richardson</persName> (<date notBefore="1811" notAfter="1834">1811&#x2013;34</date>)</head>
                <p>Cousin of <persName corresp="JR">John Ruskin</persName>, a son of <persName corresp="MR">Margaret</persName> <persName corresp="BR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s sister, Bridget</persName>, and her husband <persName corresp="GR">George Richardson</persName>, a baker. 
                    The Richardsons lived in the suburb of <placeName corresp="#CROYDON">Croydon</placeName>, near the <placeName corresp="KINGSHEAD">King&#x02BC;s Head</placeName>, the tavern operated by Margaret and <persName corresp="BR">Bridget</persName>&#x02BC;s mother, <persName corresp="MC"> Margaret Cock</persName>, and the sisters&#x02BC; birthplace. 
                    <persName corresp="MR">Margaret</persName> took <persName corresp="JR">John</persName> from a very young age to visit his <placeName corresp="CROYDON">Croydon</placeName> cousins, though he was distanced from the family, being kept on walks or in his room, 
                    except for visits by <persName corresp="CTR">Charles</persName> and his sister <persName corresp="MBR">Mary</persName> (Margaret to John James Ruskin, 30 January 1822, in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title>, 108).</ref></p>
                <p>By <date when="1829-10">October 1829</date>, <persName corresp="CTBR">Charles</persName> was employed by the publisher, <orgName corresp="SMITHELDER">Smith, Elder</orgName>, for at this time he presented <persName corresp="JR">John</persName> with a copy of 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="friendships_offering_note.php"><title type="annual" corresp="#FRIENDSHIPSOFFERING"><hi rend="italic">Friendship&#x02BC;s Offering</hi></title></ref>, 
                    the &#x201C;Literary Album and Annual Remembrancer&#x201D; that the firm had recently taken over from its initial publisher. The editor was 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="biographical" target="pringle_thomas_note.php"><persName corresp="TP">Thomas Pringle </persName>(<date notBefore="1789" notAfter="1834">1789&#x2013;1834</date>)</ref>, who was possibly introduced to the Ruskin family through the <orgName corresp="SMITHELDER">Smith, Elder</orgName> connection. 
                    According to <title type="book" corresp="#JRPRAETERITA"><hi rend="italic">Praeterita</hi></title>, <persName corresp="CTR">Charles</persName> decided to emigrate to <placeName corresp="AUSTRALIA">Australia</placeName> to join his brother, ???, 
                    because advancement at the publishing firm was unlikely. <persName corresp="CTR">Charles</persName> was drowned while the ship remained anchored off <placeName corresp="COWES">Cowes</placeName> in <date when="1834-01">January 1834</date> 
                    (see <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 35: 135-37). 
                    One wonders whether <persName corresp="TP">Pringle</persName>&#x2014;whose experience had been mixed as an immigrant to <placeName corresp="SAFRICA">South Africa</placeName>, and who coincidentally died later in the same year&#x2014;had encouraged the move.</p>
            </div>
